---
import FeatureCard from '@/components/FeatureCard.astro'
import { Heading, Markdown } from '@splendidlabz/astro'
import { chapters } from './lessons.js'
---

<section id="product" class="section">
  <div class="wrap">
    <div class="vertical">
      <Heading class="gap-4 mb-2" center>
        <h1 class="max-w-[12em]">
          <Markdown> My Entire System in Unorthodox Tailwind </Markdown>
        </h1>
        <p class="h1-subhead max-w-[42rem]">
          <Markdown inline>
            A complete system for using Tailwind and CSS together.
          </Markdown>
        </p>

        <p class="h1-subhead max-w-[42rem]">
          <Markdown inline>
            The hard part is knowing when to use Tailwind, when to use CSS, and
            when to use them both. You'll learn that system here.
          </Markdown>
        </p>
      </Heading>

      <div class="prose-responsive max-w-[37rem] mx-auto">
        <!-- prettier-ignore -->
        <Markdown>
          I've been building sites for a long time and I've never been happier with the way I write HTML and CSS today.
          
          But it took major mindset shifts to get here. I'm documenting these shifts for you inside Unorthodox Tailwind to help you get to where I am. 
        </Markdown>
      </div>

      <div
        class="grid-flex justify-center [--grow:0] max-w-mid [--cols:1] bp5:[--cols:2] mx-auto"
      >
        <FeatureCard
          title="Chapter 1: Introduction"
          showPrice={false}
          lessons={chapters[0].lessons}
          description="The mindset shifts that make everything else click."
          items={[
            'See what Tailwind brings to the table, and where it falls short',
            'The first, most important step ',
            'A simple unorthodox system',
            'A preview of the the system I use',
            'The four-part map of the whole system',
          ]}
          showButton={false}
        />

        <FeatureCard
          title="Chapter 2: Tailwind Fundamentals"
          showPrice={false}
          lessons={chapters[1].lessons}
          description="Gets you fluent in how Tailwind works. By the end you can read the docs at a glance."
          items={[
            "How Tailwind's utility system works",
            "Installing Tailwind without it's aggressive resets ",
            '7 most important utility groups',
            'Guessing the right class without checking the docs',
            'What defaults to replace, and why ',
          ]}
          showButton={false}
        />

        <FeatureCard
          title="Chapter 3: Unorthodox Fundamentals"
          showPrice={false}
          lessons={chapters[2].lessons}
          description="The core moves that make Tailwind and CSS work as one."
          items={[
            'The real ability behind Tailwind utilities',
            'The difference between components and utilities',
            'Managing specificity perfectly when using both Tailwind and CSS',
            'Debug Tailwind and CSS, fast',
            'The composable utility system, explained',
          ]}
          showButton={false}
        />

        <FeatureCard
          title="Chapter 4: The Layouts System"
          showPrice={false}
          lessons={chapters[3].lessons}
          description="Build layouts in seconds, and have HTML read like layout instead of a wall of classes."
          items={[
            'Why Tailwind shines here',
            'The 4 types of layouts: **Shell, Macro, Micro, and Positioning**',
            'Each type of layout explained in detail --- with examples and code',
            'Better variants that lets you visualize your layouts immediately across different breakpoints',
            'Tips and techniques for sections, wrappers, and containers that organizes layouts into repeatable patterns',
          ]}
          showButton={false}
        />

        <FeatureCard
          title="Chapter 5: The Typography System"
          showPrice={false}
          lessons={chapters[4].lessons}
          description="Use 3-5 typefaces in your design. And create responsive typography without complexity."
          items={[
            "Why Tailwind's typography system is weak here",
            'A consistent font-size scale that works across design software and coding projects',
            'Responsive typography without the fluid-math',
            'Making better prose',
            'Vertical rhythm demystified and simplified',
          ]}
          showButton={false}
        />

        <FeatureCard
          title="Chapter 6: The Theme System"
          showPrice={false}
          lessons={chapters[5].lessons}
          description="Handles colours, gradients, SVGs, and themes that feel clumsy in pure Tailwind."
          items={[
            "Why Tailwind's colour tokens is a strong concept",
            'The `pigment` system to style hover, active, and selected states with CSS Variables',
            'Naming conventions for states that make sense',
            'Extendable gradients with unlimited stops',
            'Coloring SVG icons with Tailwind',
          ]}
          showButton={false}
        />

        <FeatureCard
          title="Chapter 7: Useful Tools"
          showPrice={false}
          lessons={chapters[6].lessons}
          description="Deep dive into functional utilities and creating custom variants."
          items={[
            'How to functional utilities work',
            'Creating useful custom variants --- like `interact` and `interact-within`',
            'Making scaffolds for your own project',
            'Extending Tailwind on your terms',
          ]}
          showButton={false}
        />

        <FeatureCard
          title="Chapter 8: Effects"
          showPrice={false}
          lessons={chapters[7].lessons}
          description="Create visual effects like text strokes, strikethroughs, layered shadows by dropping a single utility"
          items={[
            'The mental model to build effects that are easy to use',
            'A layered elevation system you tune with variables for nicer shadows',
            'Text effects not built into most frameworks --- diagonal strikethroughs, outlined headlines, multi-line highlights, and more',
            'Transitioning shadows without the usual jank',
            'Frosted glass, border gradients, and more',
          ]}
          showButton={false}
        />

        <FeatureCard
          title="Chapter 9: Putting Everything Together"
          showPrice={false}
          lessons={chapters[8].lessons}
          description="The process, the CSS structure, and a cheatsheet you'll keep open."
          items={[
            'Decision framework on when to use Tailwind directly, when to build components, when to use CSS',
            'A CSS structure that scales',
            'Adjustments to make if you build libraries',
            'A cheatsheet that gives you the entire method at a glance',
          ]}
          showButton={false}
        />
      </div>
      <div
        class="grid-simple bp9:[--cols:2] max-w-[60rem] mx-auto gap-4 items-center"
      >
        <div class="vertical gap-2">
          <p class="text-center italic text-neutral-400">
            <Markdown inline>This is for you if...</Markdown>
          </p>
          <div
            class="prose card border-scaffold p-3 rounded-1r"
            style="border-color: var(--color-zgreen-500); background-color: var(--color-zgreen-900);"
          >
            <Markdown>
              You've used Tailwind. You know CSS. And you're done letting a
              rulebook decide how you build.
            </Markdown>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="vertical gap-2">
          <p class="text-center italic text-neutral-400">
            <Markdown inline>...but not if:</Markdown>
          </p>
          <div
            class="prose card p-3 rounded-1r"
            style="border-color: var(--color-zred-500); background-color: var(--color-zred-850);"
          >
            <Markdown>
              You want a plugin to install and forget, or you'd rather be told
              the rules than decide for yourself.
            </Markdown>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>
